content: Welcome to the Online Renju Class analysis lesson!
In the first place, this is my first teaching in the Analysis Department. I am very glad to teach here.
Now, please press "I AM HERE" button, to show that you are here.

SamSite, whywhy, callings, luwenzhe, endlessroad, AUTHOR, whte, sakura, shaoping, Fermat, wkafei, ouzo, weigui, FIFAWORLDCUP, Jasny_sokol, hobbang, Padovan, slamduk, sunrain, mayhem, sosei, Aurora, swordblue, span, H8, yyfcsd, ouyang, LiuJianping, sirasoni, dittp, zhp3410, Andry, royc, tommy, wolfzhou, moocheng, yun_shou, bm, Renju_liu_t, Intotherenju, mumax, coco_yuang, bawangwan.
Now, we are ready to begin. Today we will revise some games from Spring ORC Qualification tournament.
We will review some strategic concepts, how to play on offline tournaments.
Spring QT was an offline tournament with 40 days time limit. There were 28 participants, all of them had 20 games to play.
Maybe some of you followed this tourny.
Everybody knew that at least 16 points were required to get into top 7 and advancing to the final. So every games were very important.
So, let's discuss about how to achieve a good performance in such offline tourny.
What is the first task doing at the beginning of the tournament?
So, what would you do at the very beginning of the toury? Please write here your idea!
Check popular openings, and don't play very fast at the beginning :)
check which is the worst opening of my opponents
the openings are the most important point during the game?
First task is gathering information about opponents.
What type of information are worthy to gather?
Is it interesting to gather opponents' favourite foods or soccer teams? :-))))
only if you want to go out with them :-DDD
All information are important that will help you to win the game!
wait till the opponent set the openint first
And offering that food for him is he loses :)

Like this: opponents' result in previous tournaments, opponents' favourite opening patterns, lack of knowledge in some opening patterns, playing strength, playing style (aggressive,calm,sharp,defender), renju career...
What are the best tools to analyze opponents?
Yep, Best tools for analyse opponents are databases, e.g.: Showrenju, Renlib, Stepanov's databases etc.
And maybe most important: observing opponents' active games (in progress).
For example, you can see opponents' games on PBM server, Renju Post server, gambler.ru, ORC client etc.
really have many to be prepared
Old games not so important than newest games. Agree?
Hardest problem is unknow players...very difficult to choose opening and play against unknow players.
I encountered about this problem on Spring QT, Celie, Sunrain, Fallnavy were "dark horses" for me on the tourny :-(
so we need play at orc by unknown names :)
Well, let's see some strategic trick in offline tournaments
hmm,I want to be white horse:D
Very good strategy is "waiting style" at the beginning of the tourny. We can watch what opening patterns use our opponents against other players
When we have enough information about players, then we can draw a conclusion and we can put opening pattern on the boards!
Who would like to use this style?
if everyone thinks the same way noone will start the game, and everyone will time out
that's why i wouldn't use this style and win all the games by time :-)))
i think few player use such style in QT
but what if everybody waits there :)
After long time waiting will decesive factor the time limit, intenet access etc...
in group A of Email WC, many players use this strategy
Somebody will start because of he/she would like to win ... :)
Why so important to watch opponents' and other players' active current games?
have more time to prepare well.
Yep, Because of the renju theory change and develop day by day! This is very important.
So, you do not like to lose some games easily in the opening phase, then you need to follow all current renju activities on the world :-)))
So you need to have big eyes and ears. There are two english idiom about this
"To have eyes in the back of one's head" and "To keep one's ear to the ground" :-)))
Maybe you can understand these idioms :)
So, For example, many times I took some good renju theory info when players discussed after RC lesson time :-)
I have some other good tips for beginners to choose openings.
Do not use same opening patterns in many of games, not even that opening is balanced and promising!
if you lose one, you might lose all the same way
donot put all eggs in the same blacket
There are two reasons: you will get many same games then your opponents can easily play against you: e.g. copying the boards.
Second reason is, what you said: maybe somebody find sure win somewhere, then you will get loss in many games!
Another tip is: for example, if you have few (2-3) games with same opening patterns, and you know these patterns wins or big advantages then play it rapidly!!!
Then your opponents will fall into the trap more easily, because of they will not have enough time to learn theory or analyse the situation.
And maybe other players will not find other balanced line in that opening.
But be careful, play quick as possible, but all games will be synchronized.
My meaning is: you need to manage these games so your opponents will be traped same time.
if you are too fast with one of them, other will choose other branches
If you had 3 game as black
All are seems black win, then wait for on all boards that opponents play the worse move...
Not let him change the branches..., then you can spare the time also!!!
if there are some same patten games, you can save a lot of time:)
What is the situation, when you play few same balanced openings pattern?
So, What is the best time-table startegy in the unclear (balanced) opening patterns?
maybe try some first, and wait
If you have few same unclear opening patterns, the best way to gain best result, if you play these games asynchronously.

Namely, play one game quick (e.g. against weaker opponent) and play one game slow!
Then, you can avoid to fall into to the same trap!
Let's see an example from Spring QT.
Nick_hopper had two same games here.
What do you think, what is the evaluation of this position? Black win, white win, black advantage, white advantage, balanced?
I think, it is big black advantage. Maybe somebody know black win here.
But, I think there are many good or better 24th possibilities.
I think, the position is decided now.
Nice 30th, but 31th is very strong to connect upper and lower area!
Here, Nick_hopper realized that something not O.K. :-)
So he tried two different 32th move.
First 32th. Black has very nice win here, who would like to show us? Please say ME.
sure, it is only VCT threat
Interesting situation for VCF enthusiast: If white defend here, there is also a VCF. Can you find it?
i am wrong,only 5 stone,give up ,thx GM
Well, after 35th, the game is over.
Many players used this opening way.
What do you think, what is the evaluation of this position? Black win, white win, black advantage, white advantage, balanced?
I think, it is white win, but not easy to show everywhere the win.
Most unlucky players was here poor Andry and Aivo.
Both players losed 3-3 games here as black :(((
This is the best line, and many variations can be possible from here.
To show all branches need at least 2-3 lesson time :)))
This is very important field of the renju competition. So try to prepare novelties in the renju theory.
Like suprise moves in the current theory or defect in the old theories.
Have you ever tried to use crazy moves in the games?
But be careful, do not use same novelties in many games. Use it only one game, because of it is more risky!
Using novelties or crazy moves depend on your opponent as well.
yes, maybe just in the real games
So my advice is: Try to use supprise moves but about 20% of in your games.
Let's see an casework abut this.

It was the opening. I was Black. I was satisfied and quiet, I thought It would be easy black win :-)))
I followed theory till now.... but when I searched sure win here I got headache...
I tried with this sequence, I hoped somewhere mayhem will miss something.
I did not find it in database :(((((
Here I did find sure win.
I was lucky! Four at 20th not necessary.
So here I found the black sure win.

Maybe this will be medium HW :-)))
This variation very good for black..., but....
so i think 20-J9,it is very important to denfence
K10 can cut,but no way to denfence

Ohhh, I droped this line because of cut :)))))))))
I was alone when I played against mayhem :-)
I had two critical games: against Fifaworldcup and fallnavy.
Both games were important to decide about top 3 places!
Maybe many player saw this opening pattern.
Both game were same opening pattern! In both games, I was white.
I played slowly both games, because of at that time this position was unclear for me too.
That time, there were many same game on the PBM server in A league!
Here I knew after many analysis, I had good position! I knew white has sure win here.
All players had 20 days at this moment, but fallnavy did not played this 25th yet.
When I had only 5 days left against fifaworldcup, I played sure win move here.
Fallnavy waited.... after 2 days, he saw games was not avtive game... :-)))
But then, fallnavy had only 5 days left! He realized this 25th move was lose.
So he changed 25th, but it was too late, 5 days not enough for finding best way for black.
In long game white can easily win, because of black has big time presure (5 days - 20 days).
It was very important, that same time on PBM server this position was frozen.
For example fillipov could not find this 24th move against chinastar, and moocheng also could not find this winning 26th move against nosovs.
Moocheng losed that game as white!
i dont know how to win here
After this nice 28th everything is clear.
Fallnavy found the best defence line.
poor fallnavy didn't sleep for 5 days :-)
Same time on the spring QT, another two players also falled into this trap: Aurora and Hex77
If Aurora would had wait for this win, she can defeat fifaworldcup same way :)))
In conclusion, offline tournaments has many other strategic trick, not only playing.... :-)))
